📂 3. Dataset Description

The dataset used is expenses.csv, containing 10 rows and the following columns:

Column	Description
Date	Date of the expense transaction
Category	Expense category (e.g., Food, Travel, Shopping, Bills, etc.)
Amount	Expense amount in ₹ (Indian Rupees)

The small dataset was used to demonstrate core data-handling and visualization techniques.
In future milestones, it will be expanded to 10 K – 20 K rows for AI and forecasting tasks.

⚙️ 4. Technologies and Libraries Used
Library	Purpose
NumPy	Used for numerical computations such as total and average expenses
Pandas	Used for loading, cleaning, grouping, and summarizing data
Matplotlib	Used for visualizing data in bar and line charts
Python 3.x	Core programming language used for implementation

🧹 5. Data Preprocessing

Before analysis, the dataset underwent several preprocessing steps:

Data Loading – Imported the CSV file using pandas.read_csv().

Inspection – Displayed the first few rows with display(data.head()) to verify structure.

Conversion – Converted the “Amount” column into a NumPy array for numerical operations.

Grouping & Aggregation – Grouped data by “Category” and “Date” to calculate total expenses.

Sorting – Sorted categories by highest total to improve readability of charts.

Verification – Checked for missing or duplicate values; dataset was clean.

📊 6. Data Analysis and Visualization
🔸 Step 1 – Total and Average Expense

Calculated using NumPy:

total_expense = np.sum(amounts)
average_expense = np.mean(amounts)


Displays total and average spending across all categories.

🔸 Step 2 – Category-wise Analysis

Grouped data by category:

category_summary = data.groupby('Category')['Amount'].sum().sort_values(ascending=False)


Helps identify which expense categories have the highest totals.

🔸 Step 3 – Bar Chart: Category-wise Expense

Created a bar chart to visualize total spending per category.
The highest-spending category was highlighted in orange for emphasis.

🔸 Step 4 – Line Chart: Daily Expense Trend

Plotted daily totals to visualize how spending changes over time.

